  "text": "One study detected two interactions: One between a walkability index and individual reported reasons why people choose their neighbourhood and another between the walkability index and education. There was a positive association between a walkability index and walking for transport only for people who choose their neighbourhood because of a good perceived neighbourhood environment (closeness to job, school, shops, services or good perceived walkability) and only for people with 12 or more years of education [CITATION_1] . In a second study neighbourhood income moderated the association between walkability and physical activity. A positive association between walkability and two outcomes of average activity level and moderate-to-vigorous physical activity was only significant in low income neighbourhoods [CITATION_2] .",
